      <hedline>
        <hl1>Hillary Clinton's Choice</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Susan O Lund letter on Sept 27 article deplores woman who attacked Hillary Rodham Clinton for not leaving husband after his affair</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Fame a Two-Edged Sword for the Candidate Clinton'' (front page, Sept. 27) quotes a woman as saying she resented that Hillary Rodham Clinton wasn't strong enough to leave her husband after his affair, implying that Mrs. Clinton was a bad role model for women.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Fame a Two-Edged Sword for the Candidate Clinton'' (front page, Sept. 27) quotes a woman as saying she resented that Hillary Rodham Clinton wasn't strong enough to leave her husband after his affair, implying that Mrs. Clinton was a bad role model for women.</p>
        <p>How can anyone outside Mrs. Clinton's family begin to understand her decision? I've known plenty of women who chose divorce after their husbands' affairs, and for some, things haven't worked out so well. Conversely, there are plenty of women who have worked hard to put their marriages back together and seem stronger than ever.</p>
        <p>Leaving isn't always the right choice for women or for their children. Insisting that it is the only recourse is not only simplistic but also the height of arrogance in judging another.</p>
        <p>SUSAN O. LUND  St. Paul, Sept. 27, 2000</p>
      </block>
